2.12 Notations
Parameters are usually denoted by Greek letters
Example:
\mu - \text{population mean}
\sigma - \text{population variance}
Statistics are denoted by English letters (Capital or Simple? You will learn more of this in the “Statistical Inference” section)
Eample:
\bar{X} - \text{sample mean}
S^2 - \text{sample variance}

The value of the population parameter does not change.
Sample statistics vary from sample to sample.

6.20 5. Bayes’ Theorem
For events A and B_i with P(B_i) &gt; 0:

P(B_i \mid A) = \frac{P(A \mid B_i) \cdot P(B_i)}{\sum_{j=1}^{n} P(A \mid B_j) \cdot P(B_j)}
